"--_Francis Scott Key_, 1814.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"_The Star Spangled Banner_ was written in 1814 by Francis Scott Key at the time of the bombardment of Fort McHenry, near Baltimore, by the British.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"Key had been sent to the British squadron to negotiate the release of an American prisoner-of-war, and was detained there by the British during the engagement for fear he might reveal their plans.",1,1,1,0,1,0
The bombardment lasted all through the night.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"In his joy the following morning at seeing the American flag still flying over Fort McHenry, Key wrote the first stanza of the _Star Spangled Banner_ on the back of an old letter, which he drew from his pocket.",1,1,0,1,1,0
He finished the poem later in the day after he had been allowed to land.,1,1,0,1,1,0
"The poem was first printed as a handbill enclosed in a fancy border; but one of Key's friends, Judge Nicholson, of Baltimore, saw that the tune of _Anacreon in Heaven_, an old English drinking song, fitted the words, and the two were quickly united with astonishing success.",0,0,0,0,0,0
The old flag which prompted the poem is still in existence; it was made by Mrs Mary Pickersgill.,1,0,0,0,0,0
