"Draw the outline of your flag, making for           convenience, the width equal an even 10 units           (such as eighths or quarters or half, etc.)",0,0,0,0,0,0
so           that the length can be made 19 units.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"Get the 13 stripes outlined as follows: a) Take           your ruler and find a place marking 13 units, such           as 3-1/4 inches, or 6-1/2 or even 9-3/4 inches.",0,0,0,0,0,0
b)           Then draw the 2 lines A B and A' B'; marking off           the 13 points on each.,0,0,0,0,0,0
It does not matter where           the lines are drawn so long as they extend between           the top and bottom of the rectangle.,1,0,0,0,0,0
"c) Through           these points draw lightly, the lines for the           stripes, covering the _whole_ flag.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"Before making the final lines, block in the           union in the upper left hand corner, making its           length equal to 7.6 of the original units used for           the whole flag.",1,0,0,0,0,0
The width of the union is _seven_           stripes.,0,0,0,0,0,0
Place the stars as follows: The lines marking           the stripes may be used to mark the 6 lines of           stars.,1,0,0,0,0,0
The eight stars to a line may be determined           by dividing the length of the union into nine           parts and dropping eight perpendiculars through           the six lines already there.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"In the sketch the           line, D F and D' F' are guide lines to make the           new parallel lines.",0,0,0,0,0,0
These are made just as in the           case of A B and A' B' only containing nine units           and extending between the two sides of the union.,0,0,0,0,0,0
The stars are made at the intersection of the           lines.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"It is not necessary to put in more than one           or two, to show the shape and direction of points.",0,0,0,0,0,0
