"Many times, however, it is necessary to know how to do this oneself.",0,0,0,0,0,0
_To Dress and Clean a Chicken_--Cut off the head and draw out the pinfeathers.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"Remove hair and down by holding the fowl over a flame (a gas flame, an alcohol flame, or a piece of paper flaming in the wood or coal range), constantly changing the position until all parts of the surface have been exposed to the flame.",1,0,0,0,0,0
Cut off the feet.,1,0,0,0,0,0
"Wash the fowl thoroughly, using a small brush, in water to which a little soda has been added.",0,0,0,0,0,0
Rinse and dry.,0,0,0,0,0,0
Make a slit down the back of the neck.,0,0,0,0,0,0
Remove the crop and windpipe.,0,0,0,0,0,0
Draw down the neck skin long enough to fasten under the back.,0,0,0,0,0,0
Make a straight cut from 1/2 inch below the tip of the breastbone to the vent.,0,0,0,0,0,0
Cut around the vent.,0,0,0,0,0,0
Slip fingers in carefully around and fully loosen the entrails.,0,0,0,0,0,0
Carefully draw out the entrails.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"The lungs, lying in the cavities under the breast, and the kidneys, in the hollow near the end of the backbone, must be taken out separately.",1,0,0,0,0,0
Remove the oil sack and wash the chicken by allowing cold water to run through it.,1,0,0,0,0,0
"To clean giblets (the gizzard, the heart, and the liver) proceed as follows: Separate the gall bladder from the liver, cutting off any portion of the liver that may have a greenish tinge.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"Remove the thin membrane, the arteries, the veins and the clotted blood around the heart.",0,0,0,0,0,0
Cut the fat and the membranes from the gizzard.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"Make a gash through the thickest part of the gizzard as far as the inner lining, being careful not to pierce it.",1,0,0,0,0,0
Remove the inner sack and discard.,0,0,0,0,0,0
Wash the gizzard carefully and boil in water to use for giblet sauce.,0,0,0,0,0,0
If the chicken comes from the market dressed it should be washed carefully and any pinfeathers removed which were overlooked by the market man.,1,0,0,0,0,0
"_To Stuff, Truss and Roast a Chicken_--When the chicken is clean and prepared as directed, fill it with stuffing (described later), a little in the opening at the neck, the rest in the body cavity.",1,0,0,0,0,0
Sew up the opening with a few long stitches.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"Draw the skin of the neck smoothly down and under the back, press the wings close against the body and fold the pinions under, so that they will cross the back and hold down the skin of the neck.",1,0,0,0,0,0
Press the legs close to the body.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"Thread the trussing needle with white twine, using it double.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"Press the needle through the wing at the middle joint, pass it through the skin of the neck and back, and out again at the middle joint of the other wing.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"Return the needle through the bend of the leg at the second joint, through the body, and out at the same point on the other side; draw the cord tight and tie it with the end at the wing joint.",1,0,0,0,0,0
Thread the needle again and run it through the legs and body at the thigh bone and back at the ends of the drumsticks.,1,0,0,0,0,0
"Draw the drumstick bones close together, covering the opening made for drawing the chicken and tie the ends.",0,0,0,0,0,0
Have both knots on the same side of the chicken.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"When cooked, cut the cord on the opposite side and draw out by the knots.",0,0,0,0,0,0
Lay the stuffed and trussed chicken on its back on a rack in a roasting pan.,1,0,0,0,0,0
Lay a strip of salt pork on breast.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"Place in a hot oven until the chicken begins to brown, then lower the temperature and cook the chicken until very tender.",1,0,0,0,0,0
Baste often with the drippings in the pan.,0,0,0,0,0,0
From 3 to 4 hours will be required for a five-pound chicken.,0,0,0,0,0,0
If a fowl is used it should be steamed for 3 or 4 hours and then roasted for 1/2 hour.,0,0,0,0,0,0
