=Major Injuries and Emergencies= 1.,0,0,0,0,0,0
(a) DISLOCATIONS; (b) FRACTURES (a) _Dislocations_--In a dislocation the head of a bone is pushed or pulled out of its socket.,1,0,0,0,0,0
"A person may be falling and in trying to save himself catch hold of something in such a way that he feels a sharp, sudden, severe pain, and may even feel the head of the bone slip out at the shoulder or elbow.",1,1,1,1,1,1
When you looked at the injured part it does not look like the other side.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"If you attempt to move it you find it will no longer move as a joint does, but is stiff.",1,0,0,0,0,0
There is great pain and rapid swelling usually.,0,0,0,0,0,0
There may or may not be black and blue spots around the joint.,0,0,0,0,0,0
_Treatment_--Send for a doctor at once.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"While waiting for the doctor, place the patient in the easiest position possible, and apply hot or cold cloths, frequently changed, to the injured part.",0,0,0,0,0,0
In dislocation of the jaw it may be necessary for someone to try to replace it before the doctor arrives.,0,0,0,0,0,0
The mouth is open and the jaw fixed.,0,0,0,0,0,0
The patient may even tell you he has felt the jaw slip out of its socket.,1,0,0,0,0,0
Wrap your thumbs in cloth to prevent biting when the jaw snaps back in place.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"Place the thumbs on the tops of the lower teeth on each side, with the fingers outside, and push firmly down until the head of the bone can slip over the edge of the socket into place.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"As you feel the bone slipping into place, slide your thumbs out to the inner side of the cheek to prevent biting when the jaws snap together with the reducing of the dislocation.",1,0,0,0,0,0
(b) _Fractures_--_Broken bones_--There are two classes of fractures: 1.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"_Simple_--In a simple fracture the bone is broken, but the skin is not broken; that is, there is no outward wound.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"_Compound_--In a _compound_ fracture not only is the bone broken, but the jagged ends pierce through the skin and form an open wound.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"This makes it more dangerous as the possibility of infection by germs at the time of the accident, or afterward, is added to the difficulty of the fracture.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"_Symptoms_--As in dislocation, you should be familiar with the main symptoms of a broken bone.",0,0,0,0,0,0
When you look at the injured part it may or may not look like its mate on the other side.,1,0,0,0,0,0
In the more severe fractures it usually does not.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"When you try to move it you find more motion than there should be, if the bone has broken clear through; that is, there will seem to be a joint where no joint should be.",0,0,0,0,0,0
The least movement causes great pain.,0,0,0,0,0,0
The swelling is usually rapid.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"The discoloration (black and blue) appears later; not at once, unless there is also a superficial bruise.",0,0,0,0,0,0
The patient is unable to move the injured part.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"You may hear the grate of the ends of the bone when the part is moved, but you should not move the injured bone enough to hear this, especially if the limb is nearly straight; the detection of this sound should be left for the doctor.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"_Treatment_--Send for a doctor at once, and if it will be possible for him to arrive soon, make the patient as comfortable as possible and wait for him.",1,1,1,1,1,1
"However, if it will be some time before the doctor can arrive you should try to give such aid as will do no harm and will help the sufferer.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"You must handle the part injured and the patient with the utmost gentleness to avoid making a simple fracture into a compound one, or doing other injury, and also to give him as little additional suffering as possible.",1,1,1,1,1,1
You will need to get the clothing off the part to be sure of what you are doing.,1,0,0,0,0,0
"Rip the clothing in a seam if possible when the fracture is in an arm or leg, but if this cannot be done, you will have to cut the material.",0,0,0,0,0,0
Do not try to move the broken bone trying to get off a sleeve or other part of the clothing.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"With the greatest gentleness put the injured part, for instance, the arm or leg, as nearly as possible in the same position as the sound part, and hold it in that position by splints.",1,0,0,0,0,0
Do not use force to do this.,0,0,0,0,0,0
There is no great hurry needed to set a broken bone.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"The important point is to get it set right, and this may better be done after complete rest of several days, allowing for the passing of the inflammation.",0,0,0,0,0,0
_The Most Important What Not to Do Points for Fractures Are_: 1.,0,0,0,0,0,0
If there is reason to think a bone _may_ be broken try in all ways to prevent motion at _point_ of fracture lest it be made compound.,1,0,0,0,0,0
Do not go hunting for symptoms of fracture (such as the false point of motion or the sound crepitus) just to be sure.,0,0,0,0,0,0
The best treatment is to try to immobilize the part till the doctor comes.,0,0,0,0,0,0
_Splints_--Anything that is stiff and rigid may be used for splints.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"Shingles, boards, limbs of trees, umbrellas, heavy wire netting, etc.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"Flat splints are best, however.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"All splints should be padded, especially where they lie against a bony prominence, as for instance, the ankle or elbow joint.",1,0,0,0,0,0
If the patient is wearing heavy winter clothing this may form sufficient padding.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"If not, then other cloth, straw or leaves may be used.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"Cotton batting makes excellent padding but if this is not to be had quickly, other things can be made to do to pad the first rough splints which are applied until the patient can reach a doctor or the doctor arrives on the scene of the accident.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"In applying splints remember they must extend beyond the next joint below and the next joint above, otherwise movement of the joint will cause movement of the broken part.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"The splints are tied firmly in place with handkerchiefs, strips of cloth, or bandages, tied over splints, padding and limb.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"Do not tie tight enough to increase the pain, but just enough to hold the splints firmly.",0,0,0,0,0,0
Do not tie directly over the break.,0,0,0,0,0,0
There must be an inner and outer splint for both the arms and the legs.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"(a) SERIOUS WOUNDS; (b) SERIOUS BLEEDING Send for the doctor at once, and then stop the bleeding and keep as clean as possible till he arrives.",1,1,1,1,1,1
"In any wound with a break in the skin, there is the danger of infection or blood poisoning, as you have already learned.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"In serious wounds through the skin, flesh and blood vessels there is also the danger of severe bleeding, with the possibility of the patient's bleeding to death.",0,0,0,0,0,0
_Infection_--You already know how the germs which can cause the blood poisoning get into the wound.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"(a) by the object that makes the wound (b) from the clothing of the patient through which the wound is made (c) from the rescuer's hands (d) from the water which has not been sterilized used in washing the wound (e) from dirty dressings, that is, dirty in the sense that they have on them germs which can get into the wound and cause infection or blood poisoning.",1,0,0,0,0,0
The first two of these chances the Girl Scout will not be able to control.,0,0,0,0,0,0
The last three she can to some extent prevent.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"_Do not wash, touch or put anything into a serious wound_ unless a doctor cannot be found.",0,0,0,0,0,0
Only this sort of thing justifies running risk of infection.,0,0,0,0,0,0
Otherwise just put on a sterile dressing and bandage.,0,0,0,0,0,0
In reality washing wounds only satisfies the aesthetic sense of the operator without real benefit to the patient in many cases.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"If a wound has to be cleansed before the doctor comes use boiled water; if this cannot be had at once, use water and alcohol half and half.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"Always wash your hands thoroughly with water, soap and a nail brush, unless there is necessity for immediate help to stop bleeding which admits of no time to clean one's hands.",0,0,0,0,0,0
Be sure your nails are clean.,0,0,0,0,0,0
Try not to touch the wound with your hands unless it is absolutely necessary.,1,0,0,0,0,0
"Many wounds do not have to be washed, but dressing may be applied directly.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"Having cleansed the wound as best you can, or all that is necessary, apply sterile cloth for dressing.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"This may be gotten at a drug store in a sterile package ready for use immediately, and is very satisfactory.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"If, however, these cannot be had, remember any cloth like a folded handkerchief that has been recently washed and _ironed_ is practically sterile, especially if you unfold it carefully and apply the inside which you have not touched, to the wound.",0,0,0,0,0,0
Bind the dressing on with a bandage to keep in place until the doctor arrives.,0,0,0,0,0,0
(b) _Serious Bleeding_: It is important that you should learn what is serious bleeding and this will often help you to be cool under trying circumstances.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"As you learned in your work in minor emergencies, the bleeding from the small veins and capillaries is not usually sufficient to be dangerous, and the pressure of the dressing when put on and bandaged in place will soon stop it.",1,0,0,0,0,0
It may sometimes be necessary to put more dressing outside of that already on (called re-inforcing it) and bandage again snugly.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"But if you have made sure first that there is no large vein or artery cut, you need not be troubled for fear there will be serious bleeding before the doctor arrives.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"[Illustration: Tourniquet Showing where stone for pressing against artery is placed Loop through which stick for tightening is inserted] _Bleeding from an Artery_: If an artery is cut the blood spurts out, the size of the stream depending on the size of the artery cut.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"This is the most serious bleeding because the heart is directly behind, pumping the blood through the artery with all its power.",1,0,0,0,0,0
If it is a small artery the pressure with the finger between the cut and the heart for a few minutes will give the blood time to clot behind the finger and form a plug.,0,0,0,0,0,0
This will stop the bleeding aided by pressure of the bandage.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"If it is a larger vessel the force in the heart muscle pumping the blood will force out any plug formed by the finger there, as the finger tires too easily.",0,0,0,0,0,0
_Tourniquet_: In this case it will be necessary to put on a tourniquet to take the place of the finger until a clot can form in the vessel big enough and strong enough to prevent the force of the blood current from pushing it out.,1,0,0,0,0,0
This of course can be used only on the legs or arms.,0,0,0,0,0,0
A tourniquet is something put on to make pressure on a blood vessel to stop serious bleeding.,0,0,0,0,0,0
There are five points to remember about a tourniquet: 1.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"It must be long enough to tie around the limb--a big handkerchief, towel or wide bandage.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"There must be a pad to make the pressure over the artery greater than on the rest of the limb--a smooth stone, a darning ball, a large cork, cloth folded into a large pad or a rolled bandage.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"The pad must be so placed that the artery lies between pad and the bone on the limb, in order that the pressure may stop the flow of blood by forcing the walls of the artery together between the pad and the bone.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"Unless the tourniquet is put on tight enough, its application increases bleeding.",1,0,0,0,0,0
It is extremely rare to find a tourniquet put on tight enough.,0,0,0,0,0,0
In almost every such case removing the tourniquet will stop or partly lessen bleeding.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"A short stick or handle is needed, about a foot long, with which to twist the tourniquet sufficiently to stop the flow of blood.",0,0,0,0,0,0
Usually it cannot be twisted tightly enough by hand alone.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"Tie the twisted part firmly so it will not slip, after it has been made tight enough to stop bleeding.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"Remember, a tourniquet stops most of the circulation below it as well as in the cut artery, and must not be left in place too long for fear of injury to the rest of the limb by cutting off the circulation.",1,0,0,0,0,0
_Usually it should not be left on for more than an hour._ _Bleeding from Veins_--Bleeding from the veins is not so dangerous as from an artery.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"The blood from the heart has to go through the little capillaries before it gets into the veins, and therefore the force of the heart muscle on the blood in the veins is not so great as in the arteries.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"The blood does not spurt out, but flows out as it would from a bottle tipped on its side.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"You have already learned what to do to stop the bleeding from the smaller veins, and that it is not serious.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"From the larger veins, however, it can be very serious, and it may be necessary for you to put on a tourniquet before the doctor arrives in order to save the patient's life.",0,0,0,0,0,0
Almost always bleeding from a vein can be controlled by clean gauze or handkerchief pad and pressure by hand directly over the bleeding wound.,0,0,0,0,0,0
Tourniquets are almost never needed in bleeding from a vein.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"If necessary, it is wisest to apply them in the same way as for arterial hemorrhage and stop the circulation in the whole limb.",0,0,0,0,0,0
It is important to know in a general way where the blood vessels are in order to put the pad over them to stop the bleeding.,1,0,0,0,0,0
"Roughly speaking, the artery of the arm runs down about in a line with the inner seam of the coat.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"The large vein lies close beside it, carrying the blood back to the heart.",0,0,0,0,0,0
The artery and vein of the leg run about in a line with the inside seam of a man's trousers.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"_Stimulants_--In serious bleeding of any kind do not give stimulants until the bleeding has been stopped, as the stimulants increase the force of the heart and so increase the flow of blood.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"After the tourniquet is on and bleeding is stopped, if the patient is very weak, he may have a teaspoonful of aromatic spirits of ammonia in half a glass of water.",1,1,1,1,1,1
"(a) SHOCKS; (b) APOPLEXY; (c) CONVULSIONS (a) _Shocks_--In any injury, except the slight ones, the ends of the nerves in the skin are bruised or jarred.",0,0,0,0,0,0
They send this jar along the nerves to the very delicate brain.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"The blood is drawn from the brain into the larger blood vessels, and the result produced is called shock.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"If you have jammed your finger in a door sometime, perhaps you have felt a queer sick feeling and had to sit down.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"A cold sweat broke out all over you, and you were hardly conscious for a moment or two.",1,0,0,0,0,0
This was a mild case of shock.,0,0,0,0,0,0
In more severe injuries a shock to the brain may be very serious.,0,0,0,0,0,0
_Symptoms of Shock_--1.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"The patient may or may not be unconscious, but he may take no notice of what is going on around him.",1,1,1,1,1,1
The face is pale and clammy.,0,0,0,0,0,0
The skin is cold.,0,0,0,0,0,0
The pulse is weak.,0,0,0,0,0,0
The breathing is shallow.,0,0,0,0,0,0
In any serious injury the shock is liable to be severe and will need to be treated before the doctor arrives.,0,0,0,0,0,0
_Treatment_--Send for the doctor if serious.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"Lay the patient flat on his back with head low, so that the heart can more easily pump the blood back into the brain.",1,1,1,1,1,1
"Cover warmly; if they can be gotten, put around him several hot water bottles or bricks, being extremely careful to have them covered so that they will not burn him.",1,0,0,0,0,0
Persons suffering from shock are more easily burnt than usual.,0,0,0,0,0,0
Do not put anything hot next him unless it can be held against your own face for a minute without feeling too hot.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"Rub the arms and legs, toward the body, but under the covers.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"Give stimulants only after the patient has recovered enough to swallow, and when there is no serious bleeding.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"_Stimulants_--Strong, hot coffee, or a half teaspoonful of aromatic spirits of ammonia in a half glass of warm water.",0,0,0,0,0,0
The latter may be given if the coffee is not ready.,0,0,0,0,0,0
(b) _Apoplexy_--When a person has a stroke of apoplexy send for the doctor at once.,0,0,0,0,0,0
This condition resembles shock only in that the patient is unconscious.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"The blow to the delicate brain does not come from the outside along the nerves, but from the inside by the breaking of a blood vessel in the brain, letting the blood out into the brain tissue and forming a clot inside of the brain, and thus making pressure which produces the unconsciousness.",1,0,0,0,0,0
_Symptoms of Apoplexy_--1.,0,0,0,0,0,0
The patient is unconscious.,0,0,0,0,0,0
The face is usually flushed--red.,0,0,0,0,0,0
The skin is not cold and clammy.,0,0,0,0,0,0
The pulse is slow and full.,0,0,0,0,0,0
The breathing is snoring instead of shallow.,0,0,0,0,0,0
The pupils of the eye are usually unequally dilated.,0,0,0,0,0,0
Lay the patient flat on his back with head slightly raised.,1,1,1,1,1,1
Do not give any stimulants.,0,0,0,0,0,0
Wait for the doctor.,0,0,0,0,0,0
(c) _Convulsions_--This condition resembles the foregoing shock and apoplexy in that the patient is unconscious.,0,0,0,0,0,0
_Symptoms of Convulsions_--1.,0,0,0,0,0,0
The patient is unconscious.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"The face is usually pale at first, but not so white as in shock, and later is flushed, often even purplish.",0,0,0,0,0,0
The skin is not usually cold.,0,0,0,0,0,0
The breathing may be shallow or snoring.,0,0,0,0,0,0
There are twitchings of the muscles of the face and body or a twisting motion of the body.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"The pulse may be rapid, but is usually regular.",0,0,0,0,0,0
The mouth may be flecked with foam.,0,0,0,0,0,0
The pupils of the eye may be contracted or equally dilated.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"_Treatment_--Convulsions come from various causes, and are always serious, therefore send for the doctor at once.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"Put a wedge of some kind between the teeth if possible, the handle of a spoon protected by a cloth cover, or a rolled napkin does well.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"This is to prevent biting the tongue, which the patient is apt to do in unconsciousness with convulsive movements.",0,0,0,0,0,0
