It will do no good.,1,1,1,1,1,1
No stimulant is needed.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"(a) SUNSTROKE; (b) FREEZING (a) _Sunstroke_--Sunstroke is caused by too long exposure to excessive heat, or to the direct rays of the sun, and is much more serious than heat exhaustion, which you have already studied.",1,0,0,0,0,0
_Prevention_--Do not stay out in the direct sunlight too long on a hot summer day.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"Wear a large hat which shades the head and face well, if obliged to be in the hot sun for any length of time.",0,0,0,0,0,0
Do not wear too heavy clothing in the hot weather.,0,0,0,0,0,0
Leaves or a wet sponge in the top of the hat will help to prevent sunstroke.,0,0,0,0,0,0
Drink plenty of cool water between meals.,0,0,0,0,0,0
_Symptoms of Sunstroke_--1.,0,0,0,0,0,0
The patient is unconscious.,0,0,0,0,0,0
The face is red.,0,0,0,0,0,0
The pupils large.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"The skin very hot and dry, with _no_ perspiration.",0,0,0,0,0,0
The pulse is full and slow.,0,0,0,0,0,0
The breathing is sighing.,0,0,0,0,0,0
Get the patient into the shade where it is as cool as possible.,1,0,0,0,0,0
Send for the doctor.,0,0,0,0,0,0
Remove the greater part of the clothing.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"Apply cold water or ice to the head, face, chest and armpits.",0,0,0,0,0,0
Often the patient recovers consciousness before the doctor arrives; give cold water to drink; never stimulants.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"(b) _Freezing_--This is a much more serious condition than frostbite, which you have studied, but only because more of the body is frozen and the tissues are frozen deeper.",0,0,0,0,0,0
Much more care must therefore be taken to prevent bad effects after the thawing-out process.,0,0,0,0,0,0
_Symptoms of Freezing_--1.,0,0,0,0,0,0
The patient may or may not be unconscious.,0,0,0,0,0,0
The frozen parts are an intense white and are without any feeling or motion.,0,0,0,0,0,0
_Treatment_--Send for the doctor at once.,0,0,0,0,0,0
Take the patient into a cold room.,0,0,0,0,0,0
Remove the clothing.,0,0,0,0,0,0
Rub the body with rough cloths wet in cold water.,0,0,0,0,0,0
Very gradually increase the warmth of the water used for rubbing.,0,0,0,0,0,0
Increase the temperature of the room gradually.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"When the patient can swallow, give him stimulants.",1,1,1,1,1,1
"When the skin becomes more normal in color and the tissues are soft, showing that the blood is once more circulating properly through the frozen flesh, cover the patient warmly with hot bottles or bricks outside of the bed clothing, or wraps, and give hot drinks.",0,0,0,0,0,0
In using hot water be sure it is not too hot.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"Dog Bite[3] In the case of the dog bite we have a more or less extensive break in the skin and sometimes a deep wound in the flesh, through which the poison of hydrophobia, which is a living virus or animal poison, may be introduced, to be taken up slowly by the nerves themselves, reaching the central nervous system in about forty days.",1,0,0,0,0,0
The slowness and method of this absorption renders the use of a ligature useless and unsafe.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"The treatment for dog bite is therefore as follows: _Immediate._ Send for a physician, telling him the reason.",1,1,1,1,1,1
"While waiting, treat as any similar wound from any cause.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"If the skin is not penetrated, but scratched only, apply iodine and a sterile or wet dressing.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"If the skin is penetrated, the treatment should be the same as for a wound made by a dirty nail: that is, a small stick, such as a match, whittled to a point, with a little cotton twisted on the point, should be dipped into tincture of iodine, and twisted down into the full depth of the wound, and then done a second time.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"_Subsequent._ A physician should be consulted immediately, and if there is any suspicion of the dog being sick it should be kept under observation.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"The body of a dog that has been killed under suspicion of rabies or hydrophobia, should be sent as soon as possible to the proper authorities.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"One of the greatest discoveries in medical science is the Pasteur treatment for the prevention of hydrophobia after mad dog bite, and fortunately, provision for this treatment is so widespread that practically every one in civilized regions needing it, can have it, as is well known to all physicians.",1,0,0,0,0,0
The fact that the period of development of the disease is so long makes the possibility of prevention greater.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"It is never proper to suck a dog bite, because the merest scratch or break in the surface, even if too small to notice, will serve as a portal of entry for the living virus of rabies.",0,0,0,0,0,0
_Snake Bite._ For treatment of snake bite see page 297.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"WATER ACCIDENTS When it is possible, Girl Scouts should learn to swim well.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"It is fear when suddenly thrown into the water that causes so many of the deaths by drowning, and learning to swim well takes away this fear.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"A Girl Scout should also learn how to prevent accidents, and how best to help the victims of accidents in the water.",0,0,0,0,0,0
PREVENTION Below are five rules for preventing drowning accidents.,0,0,0,0,0,0
Do not change seats in a canoe or rowboat.,0,0,0,0,0,0
Do not rock the boat.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"Do not go out alone in a canoe, rowboat or sailboat unless you are thoroughly competent to manage such a boat, in a sudden squall or storm.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"Very cold water exhausts a swimmer much quicker than warm water, therefore do not take any chances on a long swim in cold water unless a boat accompanies you to pick you up in case of necessity.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"Be careful not to go too far out when there is a strong undertow; that is, a strong current below the surface of the water flowing relentlessly out to sea.",0,0,0,0,0,0
Always wade upstream.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"RESCUE [Illustration] When a person gives up the struggle in the water, the body goes down, and then because of its buoyancy it comes to the surface and some air is expelled from the lungs, making the body less buoyant.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"It immediately sinks again, this time a little lower, and again comes to the surface, and more air is expelled.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"This process may be repeated several times, until sufficient water is taken into the stomach and lungs to overcome the buoyancy of the body and it no longer appears at the surface; but the buoyancy is barely overcome, and therefore the body will float easily.",1,0,0,0,0,0
This can easily be utilized in saving the drowning person by making the water carry most of the weight of the body.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"To do this, place the hands on either side of the drowning person's head, and tow him floating on his back with the face above the surface of the water, while you swim on your back and keep the body away from you.",1,1,1,1,1,1
"Remember, if possible, to go with the current and thus save necessary strength.",0,0,0,0,0,0
In some cases it may be easier and safer to grasp the drowning person by the hair instead of trying to clasp the head.,1,0,0,0,0,0
"EMERGENCIES _Grips_--A drowning person is always a frightened person, and is governed by a mad instinct to grab anything which subconsciously he thinks may save his life.",1,1,0,1,1,0
Usually he is past any reasoning.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"He grabs his would-be rescuer with a death grip that is hard to break, but remember he instinctively grabs what is above the surface and will not try to grab below the shoulders.",1,1,0,1,1,0
"_Wrist Grip_--If the drowning person grasps the rescuer's wrists, the rescuer throws both hands above his head, which forces both low in the water, and then turns the leverage of his arms against the other's thumbs and breaks the grip.",1,1,1,1,1,1
"_Neck Grip_--To release a grip around the neck and shoulders from the front, immediately cover the mouth of the other with the palm of the hand, holding the nose between the first two fingers, and at the same time pull the other body toward you with the other hand, meanwhile treading water.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"Then take a full breath and apply your knee to the other's stomach quickly, thus forcing him to expel any air in his lungs and preventing him from getting more air by the hand on mouth and nostrils.",1,1,1,1,1,1
"If the grip of the drowning person does not allow use of the arms, then try to raise your arms to the level of the shoulder, thus slipping his arms to the neck and leaving your own arms free to use, as described.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"_Back Grip_--This strangle hold is perhaps the most difficult to break, and it is necessary to break it instantly if the rescuer is not also to be in the rescued class.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"Grasp the wrists of the other and push sharply back with the buttocks against the abdomen of the other, and thus make room to slip suddenly out of the encircling arms.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"If this is not successful, do not despair, but throw the head suddenly against the nose of the drowning person and then slip out of the grip before he recovers from his daze.",1,1,1,1,1,1
"It is often necessary to dive from the surface in rescuing a drowning person, and this requires practice, and should be learned thoroughly before the necessity for saving a life is presented.",0,0,0,0,0,0
Remember that to dive from the surface to a depth of more than ten feet will usually require a weight in addition to the weight of the body.,0,0,0,0,0,0
Carry a stone or other heavy object in diving.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"Then when wishing to rise to the surface, drop it and push against the bottom with the feet.",1,0,0,0,0,0
This will send the swimmer to the surface in short order.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"In carrying a weight in the water, carry it low on the body, close to the waist line, leaving one hand and both feet free for swimming.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"Or if for any reason it is necessary to swim on the back, it leaves both feet free to use as propellers.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"ARTIFICIAL RESPIRATION If the apparently drowned person is to be saved, no time must be lost in the rescue from the water or in getting the water out of him, and breathing re-established after he is brought to land.",1,1,1,1,1,1
"[Illustration] If there is a messenger handy send for a doctor at once, but in the meantime lose no time in attempting restoration.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"The best method for getting the water out of the lungs and breathing re-established is the _Schaefer Method_, because it is the simplest, requiring only one operator and no equipment.",0,0,0,0,0,0
It can be kept up alone for a long time.,0,0,0,0,0,0
Every moment is precious.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"Immediately lay the patient face downwards, with the arms extended above the head and the face to one side.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"In this position the water will run out and the tongue will fall forward by its own weight, and not give trouble by falling back and closing the entrance to the windpipe.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"Be sure there is nothing in the mouth, such as false teeth, gum, tobacco, etc.",0,0,0,0,0,0
Do not put anything under the chest.,0,0,0,0,0,0
Be sure there is no tight collar around the neck.,0,0,0,0,0,0
Kneel astride of the patient facing toward his head.,1,1,1,1,1,1
"Place your hands on the small of the patient's back, with thumbs nearly touching and the hands on the spaces between the short ribs.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"Bend slightly forward with arms rigid so that the weight of your body falls on the wrists, and makes a firm steady pressure downward on the patient while you count one, two, three, thus forcing any water and air out of the lungs.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"Then relax the pressure very quickly, snatching the hand away, and counting one-two--the chest cavity enlarges and fresh air is drawn into the lungs.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"Continue the alternate pressing and relaxing about twelve to fifteen times a minute, which empties and fills the lungs with fresh air approximately as often as he would do it naturally.",1,0,0,0,0,0
It may be necessary to work for an hour or two before a gasp shows the return of natural breathing.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"Even then the rescuer's work is not over, as it will be necessary to fill in any gaps with artificial breathing.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"When natural breathing is established, aid circulation by rubbing and by wrapping him in hot blankets and putting hot bottles around him, being careful that they are protected to prevent burning the patient.",1,1,0,1,1,0
"If at any time it is necessary to pull the tongue forward and to hold it to prevent choking, remember to put a wedge between the teeth to prevent biting.",1,0,0,0,0,0
Do not give anything liquid by mouth until the patient is conscious and can swallow readily.,0,0,0,0,0,0
Aromatic Spirits of Ammonia or Spirits of Camphor may be used on a handkerchief for the patient to smell.,1,0,0,0,0,0
The patient should be watched carefully for an hour or two even after he is considered out of danger.,1,1,1,1,1,1
ICE RESCUE Prevention: Below are two rules for preventing ice accidents: 1.,0,0,0,0,0,0
Do not skate or walk on thin ice.,0,0,0,0,0,0
Watch for air holes.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"Rescue: In trying to rescue a person who has broken through the ice, always tie a rope around your own body and have this tied to some firm object on shore.",0,0,0,0,0,0
Do not try to walk out to the rescue as the ice will probably break again under the weight of your body on so small an area as the size of your feet.,1,0,0,0,0,0
"Always get a long board, ladder, rail or limb of a tree, and either crawl out on this, which will distribute the weight of your body over a larger surface of ice, or lie flat on your stomach and crawl out, pushing the board ahead of you so that the person in the water may reach it.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"If you yourself break through the ice in attempting a rescue, remember that trying to pull yourself up over the edge of the ice only breaks it more.",1,0,0,0,0,0
If rescuers are near it is much wiser to support yourself on the edge of the ice and wait for rescue.,0,0,0,0,0,0
After getting the person out of the water use artificial respiration if necessary and bend every effort to get the patient warm and breathing properly.,0,0,0,0,0,0
ASPHYXIATION Prevention: Below are seven rules for preventing asphyxiation: 1.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"When coal stoves and furnaces are freshly filled with coal, coal gas may escape if the dampers are not properly regulated.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"See that all dampers in coal stoves and furnaces are correctly arranged before leaving them for any long time, as for the night.",1,0,0,0,0,0
Do not go to sleep in a house or room with a gas jet or gas stove turned low.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"The pressure in the pipes may change and the flame go out, or a breeze may blow out the flame leaving the gas leaking into the room.",1,0,0,0,0,0
Do not blow out a gas jet.,1,0,0,0,0,0
Be careful to turn off gas jet completely.,0,0,0,0,0,0
Report gas leaks promptly.,0,0,0,0,0,0
Charcoal stoves and braziers are especially dangerous from escaping gas and should not be used in sleeping rooms.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"Do not go into unused wells or underground sewers without first lowering a lighted candle which will go out at once if the air is very impure, because of lack of oxygen to keep it burning.",1,0,0,0,0,0
Remove the patient _at once_ to the fresh air.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"Gas is lighter than air, and therefore will not be found close to the floor and it will often be possible to crawl out when one would be overcome by the gas if he tried to walk out.",1,1,1,1,1,1
"For this reason it is sometimes best in trying to rescue anyone already unconscious from gas to tie the wrists together with a handkerchief, put his arms around your neck, and crawl out on all fours, dragging the insensible body with you, under your own body.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"If you attempt to walk out and carry the patient, cover your mouth and nose with a wet handkerchief, go very quickly, do not breathe until you reach the fresh air.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"If there is a messenger handy, send for the doctor at once, but in the meantime if necessary, perform artificial respiration as outlined under the Schaefer System in the preceding paragraphs, until the patient is restored to normal breathing.",0,0,0,0,0,0
ELECTRIC SHOCK This is caused by some part of the body coming in contact with a live electric wire.,1,0,0,0,0,0
The seriousness of the shock depends on how heavy a charge of electricity the wire is carrying at the time.,0,0,0,0,0,0
The patient is usually unable to release himself from the wire.,1,1,1,1,1,1
"The first thing to be done, if possible, is to turn off the current by means of the switch, but if this cannot be done _at once_, the patient must be rescued by pulling him away from the wire.",1,1,1,1,1,1
Remember his body will easily carry the charge to yours while he is against the wire.,1,1,0,1,1,0
"Therefore you must insulate yourself--that is, put on your hands something that will not let the electricity into your body--or stand on something that will insulate you; for instance, rubber gloves or rubber tobacco pouches, dry silk handkerchiefs, other silk garments or newspapers used in place of gloves if necessary.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"Stand on a rubber mat or on _dry boards_, or glass, or in dire necessity _dry_ clothes can be used to stand on.",0,0,0,0,0,0
They must not be wet as then they will carry the electric current through your body and you must also be rescued instead of rescuing.,1,0,0,0,0,0
Do not touch the third rail of electric railways.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"Do not catch hold of swinging wires, they may be live wires.",0,0,0,0,0,0
Report broken wires to the right authorities.,0,0,0,0,0,0
