"[Illustration: LUNCHEON FIRE] If one would have good meals cooked out of doors, and would save much time and vexation; in other words, if he wants to be comfortable in the woods, he must learn how to produce at will either (1) a quick, hot little fire that will boil water in a jiffy, and will soon burn down to embers that are not too ardent for frying; or (2) a solid bed of long-lived coals that will keep up a steady, glowing, smokeless heat for baking, roasting or slow boiling; or (3) a big log fire that will throw its heat forward on the ground, and into a tent or lean-to, and will last several hours without replenishing.",1,1,1,1,1,1
"_Luncheon Fire_--For a noonday lunch, or any other quick meal, when you have only to boil coffee and fry something, a large fire is not wanted.",0,0,0,0,0,0
