Kindling The best kindling is fat pine or the bark of the paper birch.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"Fat pine is found in the stumps and butt cuts of pine trees, particularly those that died on the stump.",0,0,0,0,0,0
The resin has collected there and dried.,0,0,0,0,0,0
This wood is usually easy to split.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"Pine knots are the tough, heavy resinous stubs of limbs that are found on dead pine trees.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"They, as well as fat pine, are almost imperishable, and those sticking out of old rotten logs are as good as any.",1,0,0,0,0,0
In collecting pine knots go to fallen trees that are almost rotted away.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"Hit the knot a lick with the pole of the axe and generally it will yield; if you must chop, cut deep to get it all and to save the axe edge.",1,0,0,0,0,0
The knots of old dead balsams are similarly used.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"Usually a dead stump of pine, spruce, or balsam, all punky on the outside, has a core very rich in resin that makes excellent kindling.",0,0,0,0,0,0
Hemlock knots are worthless and hard as glass--keep your axe out of them.,1,0,0,0,0,0
The thick bark of hemlock is good to make glowing coals in a hurry; so is that of hard woods generally.,0,0,0,0,0,0
