_Fire Regulations_--On state lands and on national forest reserves it is forbidden to use any but fallen timber for firewood.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"Different states have various other restrictions, some, I believe, not permitting trampers to light a fire in the woods at all unless accompanied by a registered guide.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"In New York the regulations prescribe that fires will be permitted for the purposes of cooking, warmth and insect smudges; but before such fires are kindled sufficient space around the spot where the fire is to be lighted must be cleared from all combustible material; and before the place is abandoned fires so lighted must be thoroughly quenched.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"In Pennsylvania forest reserves no fire may be made except in a hole or pit one foot deep, the pit being encircled by the excavated earth.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"In those of California, no fire at all may be lighted without first procuring a permit from the authorities.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"Fire regulations are posted on all public lands, and if campers disregard them they are subject to arrest.",1,0,0,0,0,0
These are wise and good laws.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"Every camper who loves the forest, and who has any regard for public interest, will do his part in obeying them to the letter.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"However, if he occupies private property where he may use his own judgment, or if he travels in the wilderness far from civilization, where there are no regulations, it will be useful for him to know something about the fuel value of all kinds of wood, green as well as dead, and for such people the following information is given: The arts of fire building are not so simple as they look.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"To practice them successfully in all sorts of wild regions we must know the different species of trees one from another, and their relative fuel values, which as we shall see, vary a great deal.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"We must know how well, or ill, each of them burns in a green state, as well as when seasoned.",0,0,0,0,0,0
It is important to discriminate between wood that makes lasting coals and such as soon dies down to ashes.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"Some kinds of wood pop violently when burning and cast out embers that may burn holes in tents and bedding or set the neighborhood afire; others burn quietly, with clear, steady flame.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"Some are stubborn to split, others almost fall apart under the axe.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"In wet weather it takes a practiced woodsman to find tinder and dry wood, and to select a natural shelter where fire can be kept going during a storm or rain or snow, when a fire is most needed.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"There are several handy little manuals by which one who has no botanical knowledge can soon learn how to identify the different species of trees by merely examining their leaves, or, late in the season, by their bark, buds and habit of growth.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"But no book gives the other information that I have referred to; so I shall offer, in the present chapter, a little rudimentary instruction in this important branch of woodcraft.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"It is convenient for our purpose to divide the trees into two great groups, hard woods and soft woods, using these terms not so loosely as lumbermen do, but drawing the line between sycamore, yellow birch, yellow pine, and slippery elm, on the one side, and red cedar, sassafras, pitch pine and white birch, on the other.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"_As a general rule_, hard woods make good, slow-burning fuel that yields lasting coals, and soft woods make a quick, hot fire that is soon spent.",0,0,0,0,0,0
