"_Best Fuel_--Best of all northern fire woods is hickory, green or dry.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"It makes a hot fire, but lasts a long time, burning down to a bed of hard coals that keep up an even, generous heat for hours.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"Hickory, by the way, is distinctly an American tree; no other region on earth produces it.",0,0,0,0,0,0
The live oak of the south is most excellent fuel; so is holly.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"Following the hickory, in fuel value, are chestnut, oak, overcup, white, blackjack, post and basket oaks, pecan, the hornbeams (ironwoods), and dogwood.",0,0,0,0,0,0
The latter burns finely to a beautiful white ash that is characteristic; apple wood does the same.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"Black birch also ranks here; it has the advantage of 'doing its own blowing,' as a Carolina mountaineer said to me, meaning that the oil in the birch assists its combustion so that the wood needs no coaxing.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"All of the birches are good fuel, ranking in about this order: Black, yellow, red, paper, and white.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"Sugar maple was the favorite fuel of our old-time hunters and surveyors because it ignites easily, burns with a clear, steady flame, and leaves good coals.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"Locust is a good, lasting fuel; it is easy to cut, and, when green, splits fairly well; the thick bark takes fire readily and the wood then burns slowly, with little flame, leaving pretty good coals; hence it is good for night wood.",1,0,0,0,0,0
Mulberry has similar qualities.,0,0,0,0,0,0
The scarlet and willow oaks are among the poorest of the hard woods for fuel.,0,0,0,0,0,0
Cherry makes only fair fuel.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"White elm is poor stuff, but slippery elm is better.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"Yellow pine burns well, as its sap is resinous instead of watery like that of the soft pines.",0,0,0,0,0,0
In some respects white ash is the best of green woods for campers fuel.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"It is easily cut and split, is lighter to tote than most other woods, and is of so dry a nature that even the green wood catches fire readily.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"It burns with clear flame, and lasts longer than any other free-burning wood of its weight.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"On a wager, I have built a bully fire from a green tree of white ash, one match, and no dry kindling.",0,0,0,0,0,0
I split some of the wood very fine and 'frilled' a few of the little sticks with my knife.,1,0,0,0,0,0
"_Soft Woods_--Most of the soft woods are good only for kindling, or for quick cooking fires, and then only when seasoned.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"For these purposes, however, some of them are superior, as they split and shave readily and catch fire easily.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"Liquidambar, magnolia, tulip, catalpa, and willow are poor fuel.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"Seasoned chestnut and yellow poplar make a hot fire, but crackle and leave no coals.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"Balsam fir, basswood, and the white and loblolly pines make quick fires, but are soon spent.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"The grey (Labrador) or jack pine is considered good fuel in the far north, where hard woods are scarce.",0,0,0,0,0,0
Seasoned tamarack is good.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"Spruce is poor fuel, although, being resinous, it kindles easily and makes a good blaze for 'branding up' a fire.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"Pitch pine, which is the most inflammable of all woods when dry and 'fat,' will scarcely burn at all in a green state.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"Sycamore and buckeye, when thoroughly seasoned, are good fuel, but will not split.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"Alder burns readily and gives out considerable heat, but is not lasting.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"The dry wood of the northern poplar (large-toothed aspen) is a favorite for cooking fires, because it gives an intense heat, with little or no smoke, lasts well, and does not blacken the utensils.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"Red cedar has similar qualities, but is rather hard to ignite and must be fed fine at the start.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"The best green soft woods for fuel are white birch, paper birch, soft maple, cottonwood, and quaking aspen.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"As a rule, the timber growing along the margins of large streams is softwood.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"Hence, driftwood is generally a poor mainstay unless there is plenty of it on the spot; but driftwood on the sea coast is good fuel.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"_Precautions_--I have already mentioned the necessity of clearing the camp ground of inflammable stuff before starting a fire on it, raking it toward a common center and burning all the dead leaves, pine needles and trash; otherwise it may catch and spread beyond your control as soon as your back is turned.",1,0,0,0,0,0
Don't build your fire against a big old punky log; it may smoulder a day or two after you have left and then burst out into flame when the breeze fans it.,1,0,0,0,0,0
"_Never_ leave a spark of fire when breaking camp, or when leaving it for the day.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"Make absolutely sure of this by drenching the campfire thoroughly, or by smothering it completely with earth or sand.",1,0,0,0,0,0
