"Amphibians           _All nature is so full that that district produces           the greatest variety which is most examined._                --_Gilbert White, Natural History of Selborne._ The group of back-boned animals next above the fishes is the Amphibians, which includes the frogs, toads, salamanders,[7] and their relatives.",1,0,0,0,0,0
The name amphibian refers to two modes of life as shown by most of the frogs and toads.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"A good example is the Common Toad, whose eggs are laid in the water.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"These eggs hatch out not into toads, but into tadpoles, which have no legs and which breathe by means of gills, as the fishes do.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"They grow rapidly, develop a pair of hind legs and then a pair of front legs, while the tail and gills are absorbed, all within a little more than a month from the time the eggs are laid.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"During this change a pair of lungs is developed, so that the toads breathe air as human beings do.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"The eggs of toads and frogs may be collected in the spring in ponds, and this remarkable change from the egg through the tadpole stage to the adult form may be observed in a simple home aquarium.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"Toads' eggs may be distinguished from those of frogs by the fact that toads' eggs are laid in strings, while frogs' eggs are laid in masses.",0,0,0,0,0,0
