"THE COMPASS           The Mariner's Compass is an instrument which shows           where the North, and other directions, are.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"Boxing           the Compass consists in enumerating the points           beginning with North and working around the circle           as follows:           NORTH           North by East           North, Northeast           Northeast by North           Northeast           Northeast by East           East, Northeast           East by North           EAST           East by South           East, Southeast           Southeast by East           Southeast           Southeast by South           South, Southeast           South by East           SOUTH           South by West           South, Southwest           Southwest by South           Southwest           Southwest by West           West, Southwest           West by South           WEST           West by North           West, Northwest           Northwest by West           Northwest           Northwest by North           North by West           NORTH           How to Find Points of Compass Without a Compass           Every Scout should be able to find the North           without a compass.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"By day the sun will tell you           where the North is, and the stars by night.",0,0,0,0,0,0
How to Tell the Points of the Compass by the Sun           The sun rises in the east and sets in the west.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"Any time before noon, if you stand facing the sun,           North is at your left hand: after noon, if you           face the sun, North is at your right hand.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"The Phoenicians, who sailed round Africa in           ancient times, noticed that when they started the           sun rose on their left-hand side--they were going           south.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"Then they reported that they got to a           strange country where the sun got up in the wrong           quarter, namely on their right hand.",1,0,0,0,0,0
The truth was           that they had gone round the Cape of Good Hope and           were steering north again up the coast of Africa.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"[Illustration: Mariner's Compass] Probably the most accurate way to find North, if you have no compass, is to use an open-faced watch.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"Holding the watch flat, turn it so that the small or hour hand points directly toward the sun.",0,0,0,0,0,0
The South will then be half way between the hour hand and the figure XII on the dial.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"Before noon the halfway point is between the hour hand and XII clockwise, and after noon it is between the hour hand and XII counter-clockwise.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"How to Find North by the Stars All stars appear to rise in the east and set in the west, which is really due to our earth turning around under them.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"But one star never moves in relation to us, and that is Polaris, the North Star, which stands still over the north pole to show us where North is.",1,0,0,0,0,0
KNOTS AND THEIR USES FOR GIRL SCOUTS It doubtless seems very strange to you that a Girl Scout should have to know how to handle a rope and tie knots according to rules.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"Most people have never dreamed that there are rules for these things; they have made knots, when necessary, in a way peculiar to themselves and have been quite surprised that the knots come out when they are expected to hold fast and hold fast when they are expected to come out.",1,0,0,0,0,0
Ropes and knots have been in use by all peoples for many years.,0,0,0,0,0,0
The rules concerning them have been developed and perfected as time has passed until now there is no question as to the usefulness of these things and the way to handle them correctly.,1,0,0,0,0,0
"As the sailors and the engineers have worked with ropes and knots more than others, it is to them that we go for our information.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"We need all we can get, for today in nearly all forms of occupation twine, cord and rope are used and knots are tied.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"As the Girl Scout who wants to be a Golden Eaglet takes up many of these occupations, she needs to know how to tie knots quickly, in the dark if necessary, and correctly, for then they will hold fast yet can be readily untied.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"These are essential requirements to be remembered, but just as important is the fact that purposes and uses of knots differ greatly.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"Every Scout should have five feet of one-quarter inch Manila rope, whipped at both ends.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"With this small piece, which only represents the much larger rope needed in many cases for practical purposes, all of the required knots can be made and nearly all of their uses demonstrated.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"Have you ever made a blanket roll, put it across your shoulder, hiked through the woods or over the hills for a sleep in the open?",1,0,0,0,0,0
Where would all your necessary articles have been if you had not tied them snugly in the roll?,1,0,0,0,0,0
Without them you would have been far from happy.,0,0,0,0,0,0
Or have you pulled a sled up a long hill over and over again for the sake of the slide down?,0,0,0,0,0,0
How about the little knots that held the rope in place--did you ever think of them?,1,0,0,0,0,0
There are many things we do for the sake of a good time where knots and rope are indispensable.,0,0,0,0,0,0
An interesting story is told by a Girl Scout who watched two men trying to hang a very large and heavy curtain which was to be used as part of the stage setting for an entertainment.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"The men tried to tie two ropes together, one of which was considerably larger than the other.",0,0,0,0,0,0
Every knot they tied was pulled out by the weight of the curtains.,0,0,0,0,0,0
Finally the men were quite ready to say It cannot be done.,0,0,0,0,0,0
It was then that the Girl Scout offered her services.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"The men looked at her doubtfully, but said, Go ahead.",0,0,0,0,0,0
Of course she tied a knot that held fast; then she had to teach it to the men.,1,0,0,0,0,0
"You see, she could be helpful, for she knew the kind of knot that would hold two ropes of unequal thickness together and knew how to make it.",1,0,0,0,0,0
Did you ever notice how few people know how to tie bundles and packages securely and neatly?,0,0,0,0,0,0
Yet this is a most helpful thing to do.,0,0,0,0,0,0
Parcels that go through the post or by express are handled roughly and unless tied with special care they are not delivered in good condition.,1,0,0,0,0,0
Sometimes we find ourselves in the midst of unusual surroundings where we can be of service if we know what to do and how to do it.,1,0,0,0,0,0
"A Scout is sometimes called upon to give First Aid, possibly to tie on splints, a bandage, or a sling; or use a life-line.",0,0,0,0,0,0
Once a boat was swept over one of the lesser falls at Niagara.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"In it were three people--a father, mother and their son.",0,0,0,0,0,0
A group of men and women standing on the bridge saw the accident; one of them ran for a rope and threw the end over the side of the bridge calling to those in the water to catch it.,1,0,0,0,0,0
"One succeeded, but the rope slipped through his hands almost immediately because there was neither a loop nor a knot to hold on to.",1,1,1,1,1,1
"Square or Reef Knot] These stories, which are true, make us realize the importance of knowing something of ropes and knots, that we may Be Prepared when our services are needed.",1,0,0,0,0,0
Parts of a Rope The three parts of a rope are:           1.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"The End, the part used in leading;           2.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"The Bight, a loop made by bending the rope back           on itself and holding it in place;           3.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"The Standing Part, the long portion of the rope           not used when tying a knot.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"Square or Reef Knot The name of the knot the purpose of which is to tie together two ends of equal thickness, either to make them fast or to lengthen a rope, is the Square or Reef knot.",0,0,0,0,0,0
It is made so that the ends come out alongside of the standing part and the knot will not jam.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"It is used when tying bundles, such as the blanket-roll, and packages; for tying on splints, fastening the ends of a sling or mending broken strings, ropes or cords, as shoestrings, clotheslines, etc.",0,0,0,0,0,0
It is the knot used more commonly than any other.,0,0,0,0,0,0
To make the Square Knot: Take an end in each hand; Cross the end in the right hand over the end in the left hand; Bend it around the rope in the left hand; Cross the end in the left hand over the end in the right hand; Bend it around the rope in the right hand; Pull tight.,1,0,0,0,0,0
"Sheet-bend Another knot that is used for tying two ends together, generally those of unequal thickness, or for fastening an end to a permanent loop, is the Sheet-bend.",0,0,0,0,0,0
Sheet Bend: Loose] [Illustration: 2b.,0,0,0,0,0,0
Sheet Bend: Drawn Tight] To make a Sheet-bend: Make in the end of the larger rope a small bight or use the permanent loop in its place; Pass the end of the smaller rope up through the bight; Under the bight; Over the bight; Under its own standing part; Pull the loops tight.,1,0,0,0,0,0
This is the way the Girl Scout tied the rope together for the stage hands.,0,0,0,0,0,0
Bowline-Knot If the people on the bridge at Niagara Falls had made a Bowline-knot in the end of the rope before throwing it as a life-line they might have saved one if not three lives.,1,0,0,0,0,0
A Bowline is used chiefly for hoisting and lowering; it can be used for a halter or with the Sheet-bend in making a guard-line or fence.,1,0,0,0,0,0
It is a knot holding fast a loop which can be made of any size and which will not jam or give.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"To make a Bowline-knot: Take the end in the right hand; Draw the rope toward you over the palm of the left hand, measuring off as much as is needed to make the required size loop; Drop the end; Make a small bight in the palm of the left hand by turning the rope toward the ends of the fingers; Take the end in the right hand; Pass it up through the bight; Back of and around the standing part; Down through the bight; Pull the end and the rope forming the loop against the standing part.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"When the Bowline is used for hoisting or lowering a person as in case of fire, the loop should be large enough to be used as a seat; it should be passed over the head and shoulders, the standing part in front of the body, to be held on to with both hands.",1,0,0,0,0,0
When using a rope for a life-line: Fasten securely one end to something that will not give.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"Make a Bowline at the other end of the line large enough to go over the head and shoulders; Hold the knot in the right hand, the end toward you; Take the standing part in the left hand, measure off about three feet of rope; Draw the rope toward you, pass it over the palm of the right hand and hold fast.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"Again measure off the same amount, draw the rope toward you, pass it over the palm of the right hand, and hold fast; Continue this process until enough rope is coiled to more than cover the distance to the person in the water.",1,0,0,0,0,0
Grasp the coil firmly in the right hand; Hold the standing part in the left hand; Draw the right arm back from the shoulder; [Illustration: 3.,1,0,0,0,0,0
"Bowline] Swing the arm forward and throw the coil out over the water to the person in distress; Make sure that the person in the water gets a firm grasp on the rope; Quickly take the standing part in both hands; Pull on the rope with a hand over hand motion, keep the line taut and pull the person to safety.",1,0,0,0,0,0
Do not make the mistake of throwing the coil up; throw it _out_ over the water.,1,0,0,0,0,0
The important points to remember when using a rope for rescue work are to fasten the free end so the rope will not slip out of reach; to coil the rope properly so it will not kink or knot when let out; and to make a Bowline large enough to go around the body.,1,0,0,0,0,0
"When a group of Scouts make a guard line, each girl makes a Bowline in the end of her rope, large enough to put her hand through, fasten her right-hand neighbor's rope to it by means of a Sheet-bend and holds her portion of the line in place by using the Bowline in her rope for a handle.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"Two Half-Hitches] Two Half-hitches are used to make fast an end of rope to a pole, post, etc.",0,0,0,0,0,0
It is a knot that can be easily undone.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"It is used for hauling, fastening awning ropes, flag ropes, etc.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"To make a Half-hitch: Take the end in the right hand; Pass the end under and around the pole; Around the standing part: Under itself, forming a bight out of which the standing part comes.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"Repeat this for the second half-hitch, using standing part in place of pole.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"Clove-Hitch] The purpose of a Clove-hitch, which is also called the Builders' Knot, is to make fast an end of rope, generally to a post or tree.",0,0,0,0,0,0
This knot holds securely and does not slip laterally.,0,0,0,0,0,0
It is of value when tethering an animal or tying a boat.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"It can be used for fastening an awning rope, tent ropes, for tying on splints or fastening the end of a bandage when it is used to confine a delirious person.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"A fence or guard-line can be made where trees or posts are available by tying the end of the rope by means of a Half-hitch to the first tree, and then using a Clove-hitch on the other trees or posts.",0,0,0,0,0,0
To tie the Clove-hitch: Take the end in the right hand; Pass it around the post; Over the standing part; Continue around the post; Under the standing part; Slip the end up through the lower loop; Pull tight.,1,0,0,0,0,0
Sheep-Shank] The purpose of a Sheep-shank is to take up slack or shorten a rope temporarily.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"It is used on tent ropes, tow lines.",0,0,0,0,0,0
To make the Sheep-shank: Cross the hands and take hold of the rope; Take up the slack by drawing the hands past each other; Hold the two long loops firmly in one hand; Make a bight in the rope between the loop and the end; Pass the loop through the bight; Do the same thing at the other end.,1,0,0,0,0,0
The knot will stay in place so long as the rope is taut.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"If it is necessary to shorten a rope when neither end is held fast, make the Sheep-shank and pass each end through the bight nearest to it.",1,0,0,0,0,0
[Illustration: Ready For Transportation or Storage] When in uniform a Girl Scout hangs her rope on a belt-hook placed in her belt or skirt-binding.,1,1,0,1,1,0
"_To have the rope in a convenient form:_ Make two loops five or six inches long at one end of the rope; Leaving a small bight at the top to go over the hook, bind the loops together by winding the standing part around them; Hold the end fast by putting it through the remaining bight.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"_To serve or whip the ends of a Scout rope so they will not fray:_ Take a piece of soft twine twelve or fourteen inches long; Make a loop two inches long at one end; Lay the loop on the rope, the end of the twine extending beyond the rope end an inch; Bind the rope and loop together by winding the standing part tightly and closely around them; Slip the end down through the loop, which must not be entirely covered by the binding; Pull the other end of the twine and draw the loop under the binding.",1,0,0,0,0,0
"As the twine will be held fast, the ends can be cut off close to the rope.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"A knot board, showing the various knots tied perfectly and names attached, ends of rope whipped, bights, loops and coils, is an interesting bit of work for a Troop of Girl Scouts to do.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"The board hung in the Troop room would be a help to new Scouts, and it could be loaned to Troops that are not registered, but are learning the Tenderfoot test, which includes knot-tying.",1,0,0,0,0,0
Glossary           Belt-hook--A double hook in the form of the letter           S. Sometimes called S-hook.,0,0,0,0,0,0
Bight--A loop made by bending a rope back on           itself and holding it in place.,1,0,0,0,0,0
"Coil--A series of rings, one on top of another,           into which a rope is wound.",0,0,0,0,0,0
Cord--A string or small rope composed of several           strands of thread or vegetable fiber twisted and           woven together.,0,0,0,0,0,0
End--One of the terminal points of that which has           more length than breadth.,0,0,0,0,0,0
The part of a rope used           in leading.,0,0,0,0,0,0
Hemp--An annual herbaceous plant.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"The fiber,           obtained from the skin or rind by rotting the           stalks of the plant under moisture is prepared in           various ways for twisting into ropes, cables, and           weaving coarse fabrics.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"Knot--An interlacement of twine, cord, rope or           other flexible material formed by twisting the           ends about each other and then drawing tight the           loop thus made.",1,0,0,0,0,0
Life-line--A rope used in rescuing; it should have           a Bowline in one end and the other end should be           secured to something that will not give.,1,0,0,0,0,0
Loop--An opening through which something can be           passed.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"Manila rope--A rope made from Manila hemp, a           fibrous material which is obtained from the leaves           of plants which grow in the Philippine Islands.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"Rope--A cord of considerable thickness,           technically over one inch in circumference.",0,0,0,0,0,0
"Ropes           are made of hemp, manila, flax, cotton or other           vegetable fiber or of iron, steel or other           metallic wire.",0,0,0,0,0,0
A rope is sometimes called a line.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"They are composed of threads which are spun or           twisted into strands and the finished ropes have           special names, according to the number of the           strands, and the various sizes are indicated by           the circumference in inches.",0,0,0,0,0,0
Standing part--The long portion of a rope not used           when tying a knot.,0,0,0,0,0,0
"String--A slender cord, a thick thread.",0,0,0,0,0,0
Twine--A double thread; a thread made of two           strands twisted.,0,0,0,0,0,0
